explanation:
For each symbol:
- OS_TaskSetPriority_Impl: The target function calls this. To judge whether the subsequent assignment (task->priority = new_priority) is redundant (i.e. executed but removable without changing behavior), you must inspect the Impl routine to see if it already updates the task table or otherwise makes the table assignment unnecessary.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: The function uses this macro/inline to obtain the task pointer from the token. Understanding how this expands (aliasing, pointer provenance) is needed to determine whether the pointer refers to the same storage that Impl might modify, and thus whether the explicit assignment is redundant.
- OS_task_table: The underlying table/object array returned by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET. You need to know its layout and whether writes elsewhere (e.g. in Impl) target the same entry.
- OS_task_internal_record_t: The record type for the task table entry. The meaning and semantics of the priority field (and any side-effects on write) are required to determine whether writing to task->priority is consequential or redundant.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: This call produces the token and return_code. Knowing its behavior (when it returns OS_SUCCESS and how it initializes token) is necessary to ensure the body is actually executed in reachable runs and to reason about any side-effects that affect subsequent operations.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: This is called unconditionally on the token path. To decide if removal of any operations changes behavior you must know whether releasing the token has side-effects overlapping with other operations (so removal would affect behavior) or whether release is redundant.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Called by OS_TaskSetPriority_Impl (per the static graph). To fully analyze Impl behavior (and thus whether the later assignment is redundant) you may need this symbol to see how the token maps to table indices and whether Impl modifies the same table entry.
- OS_PriorityRemap: Called by OS_TaskSetPriority_Impl. If Impl remaps and writes priorities (possibly updating the record), this is relevant to deciding redundancy of the explicit assignment.
- OS_object_token_t: The token type passed into Impl and used to index the object table; its definition (contents, ownership rules) is necessary to reason about aliasing, lifetime and whether Impl or release operations affect the same storage.
- OS_SUCCESS: The return-code constant used to gate execution of the body. Required to interpret control flow and whether the guarded code can execute in practice.
- osal_priority_t: The priority typedef. Knowing its representation may be needed to determine whether writing the field is a no-op (e.g. same width/encoding) or can have effects.

These symbols cover the data- and control-flow needed to decide if the assignment to task->priority (and/or any other operation in the function) is dead code: whether it is actually executed, whether its removal would change program behavior, and whether other called routines already perform the same effect.
